                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-defend2173" type="age" value="74"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18180909-314-off1729" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-off1729" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-off1729" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18180909-314-cd1730" type="crimeDate">25th of July</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-314-off1729 t18180909-314-cd1730"></join>, 49lbs. of fat, value 25s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               
                  <persName id="t18180909-314-victim2175" type="victimName">
                     John 
                     Jackson
                  <interp inst="t18180909-314-victim2175" type="surname" value="Jackson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-victim2175" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-victim2175" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-314-off1729 t18180909-314-victim2175"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>SECOND COUNT, the same, only stating it to be the property of some person or persons unknown.</p>
               <p>JOHN JACKSON. I am <rs id="t18180909-314-viclabel1731" type="occupation">master of a slaughter-house</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-314-victim2175 t18180909-314-viclabel1731"></join> in <placeName id="t18180909-314-crimeloc1732">Marshall-street, Carnaby-market</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-314-crimeloc1732" type="placeName" value="Marshall-street, Carnaby-market"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-314-crimeloc1732" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-314-off1729 t18180909-314-crimeloc1732"></join>. On the 24th of July I slaughtered twelve oxen, and hung them up in the slaughter-house. The prisoner had formerly been employed to work there. Next morning, about ten o'clock, I was going along Broad-street, opposite my slaughter-house gate, and saw him. He crossed over the way from me. He had a cloth on his shoulder. I saw some fat in it through a hole. It was in a butcher's round frock; the arms were tied up, to make it serve for a bag. I followed him up Poland-street; he went into Dring's melting-house, in Wardour-street. I then went into Mr. Dring's shop, in Oxford-street, and told his servant my suspicions. He took me to the melting-house, and showed me the fat which they said the prisoner had brought; from its appearance I knew it was stolen. It consisted of what we call toungs and shoulders of tripe, which is never cut away with the fat, it being always sold with the tripe. There was also about 21lbs. which had been taken in a hot state from the internal part of the bullock. Some pieces had the entrails on them. It was not cleaned in the usual way for sale. I got an officer, took him to Dring's shop, and found the prisoner there, with a note to receive his money for the fat. I gave him in charge to Plank, who asked him how he came by the fat. He said it was his own property; that he bought it and paid for it. He said he would not go without his money. Plank took him into custody. As we were going along, he said he would tell me where he got the fat; that he had it of two men, who were sitting at the Maidenhead public-house, New-street, close by. Plank and I went there, and found two men who worked for me. They denied it, and the magistrate discharged them; they promised to appear at the next examination, which one did, and the other absconded.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181809090099"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-314-person2176">
                  SAMUEL 
                  PLANK
               <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2176" type="surname" value="PLANK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2176" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2176" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw the prisoner at Dring's; he said he bought the fat. I asked him where, he refused to tell me. As I was taking him to the office, he said he received it of two men, who were at the Maidenhead, and that the prosecutor knew them. I found two of the prosecutor's men there and took them to the prisoner, who said they were the men. They were all three examined before the magistrate. The prisoner then denied that they were the men, or that he had said so.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-314-person2177">
                  REDIT 
                  FRESSINGFIELD
               <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2177" type="surname" value="FRESSINGFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2177" type="given" value="REDIT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2177" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a servant at Dring's melting-house, in Wardour-street. On the 25th of July, about ten o'clock in the morning, the prisoner brought two parcels of fat at two different times, which weighed six stone. I gave him an order to receive the money for it at the shop. I showed the fat to Jackson in the same state as he had brought it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-314-person2178">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HEIDENMARK
               <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2178" type="surname" value="HEIDENMARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2178" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-person2178" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutor's servant. I get up at two o'clock to work. I went to breakfast with Bailey at the public-house; the prisoner came in; Bailey said, "There is a parcel left for you, up in the corner." The prisoner took it up; he did not say who left it. I do not know what it was, or who brought it in. Bailey helped him up with it. He has since run away. I do not know what colour it was, or any thing about it.</p>
               <p>SAMUEL PLANK re-examined. It was with great difficulty I could get the last witness to attend before the Grand Jury, or to be examined before the magistrate.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had agreed to call for it at the public-house. I was taken, and told them two men gave it to me. The officer took the wrong two men.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-314-verdict1733" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18180909-314-verdict1733" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 74.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-314-punish1734" type="punishmentDescription">
